@NODE About "xMAME GUI - About"
This is a GUI for the OS4 xMAME ports made by Steffen Häuser. It supports
xMAME, xNeoMAME and xCpMAME.
@ENDNODE

@NODE InstRun "xMAME GUI - Installation & Running"
The program should come in a directory called "xmamegui". You can simply move
it to any place you like. It will search for the MAME executables and the
installed ROM's in the MAME: directory.
When you start the GUI the first time, it will create a file called "gamelist"
in the MAME: directory. The file is used for displaying the full names of the
ROM's. This is done by running xMAME.SDL (if it exists) with the -listfull
option, so it can take a few seconds.

Tooltypes:
WIDTH=n: The width of the GUI window on startup
HEIGHT=n: The height of the GUI window on startup
SCREENSHOTWIDTH=n: The maximum width of the screenshot display
SCREENSHOTHEIGHT=n: The maximum height of the screenshot display
To turn off the screenshot display, set at least one of the screenshot sizes
to 0.
Screenshots are searched for as MAME:{game}.png. You can create an ingame
screenshot by pressing F12 within xMAME.
AUTOLOADGAMEPREFS: If present, the GUI will automatically load the individual
  prefs of the games when clicking on them

Shell arguments:
WIDTH/N: The width of the GUI window on startup
HEIGHT/N: The height of the GUI window on startup
SCREENSHOTWIDTH/N: The maximum width of the screenshot display
SCREENSHOTHEIGHT/N: The maximum height of the screenshot display
To turn off the screenshot display, set at least one of the screenshot sizes
to 0.
Screenshots are searched for as MAME:{game}.png. You can create an ingame
screenshot by pressing F12 within xMAME.
AUTOLOADGAMEPREFS/T: If active, the GUI will automatically load the individual
  prefs of the games when clicking on them
@ENDNODE

@NODE GUIUsage "xMAME GUI - GUI Usage"
- If you have more than one MAME executable installed, there will be a chooser
  gadget where you can select which one to start.

- Frameskip: The checkbox turns frameskip on and off and the slider gadget
  chooses how many frames should be skipped. Only available if auto frameskip
  is off.

- Auto frameskip: Enable/Disable automatic skipping of frames. Only available
  if frameskip is off.

- Fullscreen: Runs the emulation in an own screen when turned on, otherwise it
  will open a window on the Workbench.

- Scale X: The display will be scaled horizontally by the factor entered here.
  You can enter a floating point value between 0.1 and 8. Non-integer values
  only make sense for vector games.

- Scale Y: The display will be scaled vertically by the factor entered here.
  See Scale X for details.

- Scale effect: You can choose between several effects that can be used for
  scaling.

- Artwork: If selected and if there is an artwork file in the MAME:artwork
  directory, some artwork will be displayed on the game screen depending on
  the Background, Overlay and Bezel settings.

- Background Artwork: Turns the background artwork on or off. Only selectable
  if the Artwork setting is activated.
- Overlay Artwork: Turns the overlay artwork on or off. Only selectable if the
  Artwork setting is activated.
- Bezel Artwork: Turns the bezel artwork on or off. Only selectable if the
  Artwork setting is activated.

- Sample freq.: The sample frequency for the sound output (8000-48000).

- ROM's chooser: This chooser determines which ROM's are displayed in the list
  view below it. You have five choices:
  Available ROM's: Will display all the ROM's found in the MAME:roms/
    directory if they are not hidden.
  Preferred ROM's: You can put the ROM's that you like into this list.
  Working ROM's: You can put the ROM's that are working into this list.
  Non-Working ROM's: You can put the ROM's that are not working into this list.
    A ROM cannot be in the Working and in the Non-Working list at the same
    time.
  Hidden ROM's: The ROM's that you put in here are hidden from the other lists.
    You can make them appear again, if you delete the ROM's from this list.
  The lists can be changed with the five small buttons below the listview.
  Their state will be automatically saved into a file called "romlists" in the
  MAME: directory when you start the emulation or when you quit the GUI.

- ROM's listview: A list of ROM's as determined by the ROM's chooser is
  displayed here. You can choose a game by clicking on its name. If the
  automatic loading of game prefs is active, clicking on a game will also load
  its individual options.
  There might also be some icons in front of a ROM's name:
  - Heart: The ROM is contained within the Preferred ROM's list.
  - Checkmark: The ROM is contained within the Working ROM's list
  - Flash: The ROM is contained within the Non-Working ROM's list
  - P: The ROM has its own prefs file in MAME:rc/

- Heart button: Puts the selected ROM into the Preferred ROM's list.
- Checkmark button: Puts the selected ROM into the Working ROM's list. If it is
  contained within the Non-Working ROM's list, it will be removed from there.
- Flash button: Puts the selected ROM into the Non-Working ROM's list. If it is
  contained within the Working ROM's list, it will be removed from there.
- Disappear button: Puts the selected ROM into the Hidden ROM's list. The ROM
  will disappear from the four other lists until you delete it from the Hidden
  ROM's list again.
- X button: Deletes the ROM from the currently selected list. You can't delete
  ROM's from the Available ROM's list, so you will always be able to access
  every ROM from either the Available ROM's list or the Hidden ROM's list.

- Load Game Prefs: Loads the options for the ROM that is currently selected in
  the "Available ROM's" list. The options are loaded from a file called
  "MAME:rc/{ROM}rc" where {ROM} is the name of the selected ROM.

- Save Game Prefs: Saves the options for the ROM that is currently selected in
  the "Available ROM's" list. The options are saved in a file called
  "MAME:rc/{ROM}rc" where {ROM} is the name of the selected ROM.
  This way you can have individual preferences for each game. If the directory
  "MAME:rc" doesn't exist, it is automatically created.
  Note: Options that were present in the prefs file and that are not supported
  by the GUI will be left untouched when saving.

- Delete Game Prefs: Deletes the prefs file of the ROM that is currently
  selected in the "Available ROM's" list.
  Warning: There is no safety requester when you press this button. I thought,
  the prefs are easily reconstructable and such a requester would annoy more
  than it would help. If you want such a requester, feel free to write me.

- Start MAME: Starts the emulation with the selected options.

- Load Prefs: Loads the options stored in the file MAME:xmamerc.

- Save Prefs: Writes the selected options into the file MAME:xmamerc.
  Note: Options that are not supported by the GUI will be left untouched when
  saving.

- Quit: Closes the GUI.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MenuUsage "xMAME GUI - Menu Usage"
- Project:
  - Start MAME: Starts the emulation with the selected options.
  - Create game list file: Starts xMAME.SDL with the -listfull option in order
    to create a file called "gamelist". This file is used for displaying the
    full names of the ROM's in the ROM list viewer. This option is only
    available if there is an xMAME.SDL executable in the MAME: directory. The
    option will not have an effect on the ROM list viewer until you restart
    the GUI.
    Note: The GUI will create such a file automatically on startup if it
    doesn't exist. So you will only really need this option when xMAME is
    updated and supports new games.
  - Quit: Closes the GUI.

- Prefs:
  - Auto-load game prefs: If active, clicking on a ROM in the "Available
    ROM's" list will automatically load the individual prefs of the ROM if
    present.
  - Load Prefs: Loads the options stored in the file MAME:xmamerc.
  - Save Prefs: Writes the selected options into the file MAME:xmamerc.
    Note: Options that are not supported by the GUI will be left untouched when
    saving.
@ENDNODE

@NODE History "xMAME GUI - History"
v0.13 (20.06.2005):
	New display for screenshots.
	Source code cleanup.
v0.12 (15.03.2005):
	The MAME output window is closed when closing the GUI.
	New banner at the top of the window (thanks Restore2003 and Toaks)
	Made compatible with v0.92 of the MAME ports. I had to remove the sound,
	and the screen resolution options for this.
v0.11 (26.12.2004):
	New options: Artwork, Background, Overlay, Bezel
	Bugfix: After starting, the working status of ROM's was not shown in the
	preferred list
v0.10 (21.11.2004):
	Added some cute and helpful little images into the ROM lists
	Added a "Delete Game Prefs" button
	Removed a bug that caused that a ROM was not selected when inserting it
	into an empty list by unhiding it (did you understand that?)
	Fixed a bug that could cause a crash when loading or saving game prefs
v0.9 (19.10.2004):
	Slightly cleaner code
	Removed bug that caused a crash with the first OS4 prerelease update
	ZIP files with upper case suffix are now recognized
	Added Scale X, Scale Y and Scale effect options
v0.8 (08.09.2004):
	ROM's can be arranged in several lists
v0.7 (22.08.2004):
	Each ROM can have its individual options now
	New option: Screen mode
	Memory leak fixed
	Small change and bugfix in saving of prefs
	Method of tool type reading changed
v0.6 (08.08.2004):
	ROM's are now displayed by their full name
	Menu added
	I have finally drawn a Workbench icon for this thing
v0.5 (30.06.2004):
	Reduced the max frameskip value to 11
	Changed sorting algorithm to ignore case
	Added sample frequency option
v0.4 (22.06.2004):
	Added support for zipped ROM's
	ROM list is sorted
v0.3 (19.06.2004):
	Native OS4 version
v0.2 (10.04.2004):
	Added several options
	Added WITH/HEIGHT tooltypes
v0.1 (01.04.2004):
	Initial version
@ENDNODE

@NODE Future "xMAME GUI - Future"
Following are features that have been requested. I see what I can do, but I
don't promise anything.

- Automatical selection of the MAME executable (xMAME, xNeoMAME or xCpMAME)
- Localisation
@ENDNODE

